VSymphony extraordinaire
p3
sVnews
p4
VFulfilling its agenda of organising a music concert every last Friday, Visakha Music Academy featured a violin duet in Kalabharati. Hosabally brothers K. Venkataram, a disciple of violin maestro Lalgudi G. Jayaraman and his younger brother Subbarao, who is being trained by him, were the artistes.Getting fully warmed up, playing theValaji varnamin the two tempos, they renderedVatapiganapathimbhaje(Hamsadhwani) withswaramvery briskly. Then, after rendering the rarely heard composition,Parihasakamaof Thyagaraja (Vanaspati Asampoorna vivadi melam, fourth in the first Induchakra ofVenkatamakhi Melakartascheme) avoiding thevivadiattribute with the usage of discerningly chosen phraseology inaalapanaby the elderbrother Venkataram, they playedEnthanerchina(Suddhadhanyasi) with mellifluousaalapanaby Subbarao,Mariveregathi(Anandabhairavi) andChentanesadaa(Kuntalavarali) before exquisitely elaboratingRamaneeSamanamevaru(Kharaharapriya). Then after playingRaghuvamsa(Kadanakutuhalam) in a scintillating tempo, they brought out a well elaborated and eruditely structuredragam,tanamandpallaviin Chaturasratriputa concluded with vibratingswaram.Local artiste Dhanvada Dharmarao on mridangam and D. Ramakrishna from Tenali on ghatam provided contributory accompaniment and also executed a scholarlyThani. An occasional lapse of synchrony between bowing and fingering notwithstanding, the elder brother with his scholarly and the younger one with his dulcet hand, proved to be complimenting each other aesthetically.
